:"County Kildare, Ierland","Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1386–26 July 1439":"about 1386–26 July 1439","1386–1439":"1386–1439","1385–1427":"1385–1427","1421–1477":"1421–1477","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","26 July 1439":"26 July 1439","1477":"1477","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","17 October 1427":"17 October 1427","about 1386":"about 1386","1439":"1439","1427":"1427","Maynooth, Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland","Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, England","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Ireland","Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Herne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hearn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hearn","meanings":["Irish (Waterford and Kilkenny): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEachthighearna</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachthighearna</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘lord of horses’, from <i>each</i> ‘horse’ + <i>tighearna</i> ‘master, lord’.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>herne</i>, <i>hirne</i>, or <i>hurne</i>, from Old English <i>hyrne</i> ‘nook or corner of land’ (i.e. an out-of-the-way, secluded place) or ‘bend of a river’. The name may also be habitational, from Herne (Kent), Hurn (Dorset), or Hirn (Hampshire), with the same etymology as the topographic term. In post-medieval English pronunciation the three forms have converged and the spellings become interchangeable. <i>Hurn</i> may sometimes have been pronounced and spelled the same as the surname   Horn  .","English: habitational name from Herne in Tottington, Bedfordshire, so called from the dative plural (originally used after a preposition) of Old English <i>hær</i> ‘stone’, i.e. ‘at the stones’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de la Herne was born about 1386, in Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland as the daughter of Ulick MacRichard De Burgh. She had at least 1 son with John Fitzmaurice Fitzgerald 6th Earl of Kildare. She died on 26 July 1439, in Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1386–26 July 1439":"umbes 1386–26. juuli 1439","1386–1439":"1386–1439","1385–1427":"1385–1427","1421–1477":"1421–1477","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","26 July 1439":"26. juuli 1439","1477":"1477","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","17 October 1427":"17. oktoober 1427","about 1386":"umbes 1386","1439":"1439","1427":"1427","Maynooth, Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, England","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Iirimaa","Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1386–26 July 1439":"noin 1386–26. heinäkuuta 1439","1386–1439":"1386–1439","1385–1427":"1385–1427","1421–1477":"1421–1477","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","26 July 1439":"26. heinäkuuta 1439","1477":"1477","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","17 October 1427":"17. lokakuuta 1427","about 1386":"noin 1386","1439":"1439","1427":"1427","Maynooth, Kildare, Ireland":"Ma